      "explanation": "<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:NaN\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>F+xF- Mating</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Hfr conjugation</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>F\u2019 conjugation</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<ul>\n<li>The F+ cell donor or male <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ff3e9793d01692777182b598b4a090\">bacterium</span> contains the F factor <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"795d6c91ea16927771954ebce2fadf\">plasmid</span> and encodes for sex <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8478f01ddb1692777195c325c66204\">pilus</span> formation and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"795d6c91ea16927771954ebce2fadf\">plasmid</span> transfer.</li>\n<li>During conjugation, the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e21a0b4b9f1692777202c41277aa69\">F pilus</span> forms a bridge to transfer a copy of the F factor <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"795d6c91ea16927771954ebce2fadf\">plasmid</span> to the F\u207b recipient cell, converting it into an F+ cell.</li>\n<li>This process allows the new F+ cell also to initiate <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5bf9387ee91692777185685e187e76\">conjugation</span> with other F\u207b cells.</li>\n<li><strong>F+ x F\u207b = F+</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<ul>\n<li>The F factor <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"795d6c91ea16927771954ebce2fadf\">plasmid</span> can integrate into the bacterial <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7157c1f59916927771846116d74646\">chromosome</span> and act as an episome, forming <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"765059c85b1692777189951ea50acb\">Hfr</span> cells (high-frequency <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3a379aaafc1692777197e1f873883d\">recombination</span> cells).</li>\n<li>During conjugation, only a portion of the chromosomal genes and part of the F factor are transferred to the F\u207b recipient cell.</li>\n<li>F\u207b recipient does not become an F+ cell because the complete F factor is not transferred.</li>\n<li><strong>Hfr with F\u207b = rF\u207b</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<ul>\n<li>F factor can revert to a free state and carry adjacent chromosomal DNA, forming an F' factor.</li>\n<li>When an F' cell conjugates with an F\u207b recipient, it transfers both the F factor and the incorporated chromosomal DNA, converting the recipient into an F' cell.</li>\n<li><strong>F' x F = F' and F'.</strong><strong> </strong></li>\n<li>This process is known as sexduction.</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n\n\n<p style='font-size: 10px; color: #808080; font-style: italic;'></p>",
